etymologies: early 17th century; earliest use found in John Marston (bap. 1576, d. 1634), poet and playwright. From over- + jump

definitions: To jump over (a thing). Now chiefly figurative: to transcend, overleap. Also (occasionally) without object.
Especially of a horse: to jump too far or too high over (a fence, etc.). Also with object (reflexive): to jump further than one's strength allows.
